LAGOS – The Ghana Health Service has announced the preliminary finding of two cases of Marburg Virus Disease (MVD) in the country’s Ashanti Region. According to a statement signed by Dr Patric Kuma-aboagye, Director General, Ghana Health Service, dated July 7, 2022 made available to Sunday INDEPENDENT, the government said the disease was suspected following the identification of two persons who met the case definition for the acute case of the disease at the Ashanti Region. It said that blood samples of the suspected victims were sent the, adding that preliminary results suggested the infection was due to the Marburg virus. It said: “They sent for confirmation at the Institute Pasteur in Dakar, Senegal, with the support of the World Health Organization (WHO). No new cases have been reported since the two samples were taken two weeks ago. “In addition, 34 contacts of the two cases have been identified and are currently under quarantine and being monitored by the Ashanti Regional Health Directorate of the Ghana Health Service. “The Ashanti Regional Health Directorate with support from the Ghana Health Service Headquarters is currently conducting further investigations on the cases and contacts. “Information about the Marburg Virus Disease is rare, but severe hemorrhagic fever that affects both humans and non-human with primates and body fluids. It is caused by the Marburg virus. “It is transmitted by infected persons or animals through blood and other discharges from the affected person or animal. The incubation period for the disease is two to POLL 21 days. “Treatment is symptomatic. There is currently no vaccine available. Prospective cases may present with fever, bloody diarrhea, bleeding from the gums, bleeding into the skin, bleeding into eyes and bloody urine. “The public is hereby advised to be on the lookout for any of the above symptoms and report to the nearest health facility.”